
UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Complete user authentication system including email/password registration with input validation and error handling, secure login with JWT session tokens, password recovery via email with secure reset links, optional social login providers (Google, GitHub, Microsoft, Apple), email verification flow with confirmation codes or magic links, rate limiting on auth endpoints to prevent brute force attacks, and session management with automatic token refresh. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Essential for ANY SaaS that needs to identify individual users, protect private data, or offer personalized experiences. Required whenever users need to save data, access a dashboard, or have any form of personal workspace. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Signup form with email/password validation, login page with remember-me option, forgot password flow with email delivery, account verification page, social OAuth integration, session persistence across browser refreshes, logout functionality, and optional two-factor authentication setup. EXAMPLES: A project management tool needs auth so each user sees only their projects. An e-commerce SaaS needs auth for order history and saved carts. A CRM needs auth to restrict data access per sales rep. A learning platform needs auth to track course progress per student.' WHERE feature_id = 'auth';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'User profile management system allowing each authenticated user to view and edit their personal information, preferences, and account settings. Includes profile page with editable fields (name, email, phone, avatar/photo upload, bio), account settings page for changing password and notification preferences, and a public or semi-public profile view for other users to see. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for any SaaS where users have a personal identity within the platform — marketplaces, social platforms, collaboration tools, or any product where users interact with each other or need to customize their experience. Also needed when the product displays user names, avatars, or roles anywhere in the UI. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Profile edit form with field validation, avatar/photo upload with image cropping, account settings page, password change flow, notification preference toggles, and optionally a public profile page. Stores data in a profiles table linked to auth user IDs. EXAMPLES: A freelancer marketplace shows profiles to clients. A team collaboration tool displays user names and avatars in comments. A SaaS with multi-user accounts needs profiles so admins can see who did what. An e-learning platform shows instructor profiles on course pages.' WHERE feature_id = 'profiles';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Core data management operations (Create, Read, Update, Delete) for the main entities of the application. This is the foundational data layer that allows users to manage the primary objects of the SaaS — whether those are tasks, products, contacts, invoices, posts, listings, or any domain-specific entity. Includes database table design, API endpoints or direct database queries for each operation, form UIs for creating and editing records, list/table views for browsing records, detail views for individual records, and delete confirmation flows. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for virtually EVERY SaaS application. If the product has any form of content or data that users create, view, edit, or delete, this feature is needed. The only exception would be a purely static informational site. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Database schema design for core entities, insert/update/delete operations with proper validation, list views with pagination, detail/edit forms, optimistic UI updates, error handling for failed operations, and data integrity constraints (unique fields, required fields, foreign keys). EXAMPLES: A CRM needs CRUD for contacts, deals, and activities. A project management tool needs CRUD for projects, tasks, and milestones. An inventory system needs CRUD for products, categories, and suppliers. A booking platform needs CRUD for listings, reservations, and reviews.' WHERE feature_id = 'crud';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Basic analytics dashboard showing key performance metrics and simple charts about the application usage and business performance. Includes a main dashboard page with summary cards (total users, revenue, active sessions, conversion rates), basic line/bar/pie charts for trends over time, and simple data tables with the most recent activity. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Important for any SaaS where the business owner or admin needs visibility into how the product is performing — user signups over time, revenue trends, feature adoption, or operational metrics. Also relevant for B2B SaaS where customers themselves need to see analytics about their own data (e.g., a marketing tool showing campaign performance). TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Dashboard page with metric cards, basic chart library integration (recharts, chart.js), date range selector (last 7 days, 30 days, etc.), data aggregation queries, simple KPI calculations, and optionally a CSV export for the displayed data. EXAMPLES: An e-commerce SaaS shows daily orders, revenue, and top products. A SaaS admin panel shows user signups, active users, and churn rate. A social media tool shows post reach and engagement metrics. A CRM shows pipeline value and deal conversion rates.' WHERE feature_id = 'reporting';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Automated email notification system that sends transactional emails to users when important events occur within the application. Includes welcome emails on signup, password reset emails, order/booking confirmations, status change notifications (e.g., "your request was approved"), reminder emails (e.g., upcoming deadlines, expiring trials), and admin alert emails (e.g., new user registered, payment failed). WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for any SaaS that needs to communicate with users outside the application. Essential when users need to be informed about actions taken on their account, status changes, or time-sensitive events. Also important for re-engagement (trial expiring, inactive user reminders). TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Email service integration (Resend, SendGrid, AWS SES), HTML email templates with responsive design, email queue system for reliable delivery, template variables for personalization (user name, action details), unsubscribe links for compliance, email delivery tracking (sent, opened, bounced), and rate limiting to avoid spam classification. EXAMPLES: A marketplace sends order confirmation and shipping updates. A project tool sends deadline reminders and task assignment notifications. A SaaS sends trial expiration warnings and upgrade prompts. A booking platform sends appointment confirmations and cancellation notices.' WHERE feature_id = 'notifications';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Administrative interface for platform operators to manage users, content, and system configuration. Includes a protected admin area with user management (view all users, edit roles, disable/delete accounts), content moderation tools, system settings and configuration panels, and basic operational dashboards. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for any SaaS that has a team operating the platform behind the scenes. Needed when there are users to manage, content to moderate, settings to configure, or operational metrics to monitor. Even solo-founder SaaS products benefit from an admin panel for user management and troubleshooting. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Admin-only route protection with role-based access, user list with search/filter/pagination, user detail view with edit capabilities, role assignment interface, content management tables, system configuration forms, activity logs viewer, and bulk action capabilities (e.g., disable multiple users). EXAMPLES: A marketplace needs admin to approve seller listings and handle disputes. A SaaS platform needs admin to manage subscriptions and view billing issues. A content platform needs admin to moderate posts and manage categories. A B2B tool needs admin to manage organization accounts and feature flags.' WHERE feature_id = 'admin';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Fully responsive web application design that adapts seamlessly to all screen sizes — mobile phones, tablets, and desktop monitors. Includes responsive layout system using CSS Grid/Flexbox, mobile-first design approach, touch-friendly interactive elements, responsive navigation (hamburger menu on mobile, full nav on desktop), optimized images and assets for different screen sizes, and proper viewport configuration. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Should be included in virtually EVERY SaaS application. Mobile traffic accounts for 50%+ of web usage, so any customer-facing application needs to work well on mobile. The only exception might be highly specialized enterprise tools designed exclusively for desktop use (e.g., video editing, CAD software). TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Responsive CSS framework (Tailwind CSS breakpoints), mobile navigation component (drawer/hamburger menu), responsive data tables (horizontal scroll or card layout on mobile), touch-optimized buttons and form inputs (minimum 44px tap targets), responsive images with srcset, viewport meta tag configuration, and testing across breakpoints (320px, 768px, 1024px, 1440px). EXAMPLES: A CRM must be usable on phones for sales reps in the field. An e-commerce platform must have a mobile shopping experience. A project management tool needs mobile access for on-the-go updates. A booking platform must allow mobile reservations.' WHERE feature_id = 'responsive';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Essential security measures to protect user data and prevent common web vulnerabilities. Includes HTTPS enforcement, input validation and sanitization on all forms, protection against SQL injection and XSS attacks, CSRF token protection, secure HTTP headers (Content-Security-Policy, X-Frame-Options, HSTS), rate limiting on sensitive endpoints (login, API), secure password hashing, data encryption at rest and in transit, and basic audit logging for sensitive operations. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Should be included in EVERY SaaS application without exception. Any application that handles user data, processes payments, or stores sensitive information requires these baseline security measures. This is non-negotiable for production applications. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: HTTPS/TLS configuration, input validation middleware, parameterized database queries, CSRF protection tokens, secure HTTP response headers, rate limiting middleware (e.g., 5 login attempts per minute), bcrypt or argon2 password hashing, environment variable management for secrets, CORS configuration, and security-focused error handling (no stack traces in production). EXAMPLES: Every SaaS needs input validation to prevent malicious data. Every login system needs rate limiting against brute force. Every API needs CORS and authentication headers. Every database operation needs parameterized queries to prevent injection.' WHERE feature_id = 'security';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Interactive analytics dashboard with advanced data visualization, customizable date ranges, multiple chart types, drill-down capabilities, and data export functionality. Goes beyond basic reporting by offering interactive charts (click to filter, hover for details), comparison views (this period vs. previous period), customizable widgets that users can arrange, saved dashboard configurations, and scheduled report delivery via email. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Important for data-driven SaaS products where users need deep insights into their performance — marketing platforms, sales tools, financial software, operational dashboards, or any B2B product where customers make decisions based on data. Also needed when the basic reporting feature is insufficient for the depth of analysis users require. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Advanced charting library with interactive features (recharts, D3.js), date range picker with presets and custom ranges, chart type selector (line, bar, area, pie, heatmap), data filtering and drill-down interactions, dashboard layout with draggable/resizable widgets, saved dashboard state per user, data export to CSV/Excel/PDF, real-time data refresh, comparison mode (period over period), and cohort analysis views. EXAMPLES: A marketing SaaS shows campaign performance with drill-down by channel, audience, and creative. A SaaS platform shows MRR trends, churn analysis, and cohort retention. An e-commerce tool shows sales funnels with conversion at each step. A HR platform shows hiring pipeline metrics with department breakdowns.' WHERE feature_id = 'advancedAnalytics';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Integration layer connecting the SaaS with external third-party services and APIs. Includes pre-built connectors for common services (CRMs like Salesforce/HubSpot, communication tools like Slack/Teams, payment processors like Stripe, email services like Mailchimp/SendGrid, cloud storage like Google Drive/Dropbox), a standardized integration framework for adding new connections, OAuth flow for authorizing external accounts, webhook receivers for incoming data, and API credential management. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Critical for any SaaS that needs to fit into the user existing tool ecosystem. Required when users expect to connect their CRM, email marketing, accounting, or communication tools. Essential for B2B SaaS where enterprises already have established tool stacks. Also needed when the product needs to pull data from or push data to external systems. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: OAuth 2.0 authorization flows for each provider, secure API credential storage (encrypted), webhook endpoint receivers with signature verification, API client wrappers for each integration, retry logic with exponential backoff for failed API calls, rate limit handling per provider, integration settings UI per user/organization, connection health monitoring, and data mapping/transformation layer between systems. EXAMPLES: A CRM integrates with email marketing (Mailchimp) to sync contacts. A project tool integrates with Slack for task notifications. An invoicing SaaS integrates with accounting software (QuickBooks, Xero). A recruitment platform integrates with LinkedIn and job boards for posting.' WHERE feature_id = 'apiIntegrations';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Complete payment processing and subscription billing system enabling the SaaS to charge users for services. Includes integration with payment processors (Stripe, PayPal), subscription plan management with multiple tiers, recurring billing with automatic charge, one-time payment support, invoice generation and history, payment method management (add/remove credit cards), trial period handling with automatic conversion, promo code/coupon system, failed payment retry logic (dunning), and subscription lifecycle management (upgrade, downgrade, cancel, pause). WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for any SaaS that charges users money — whether through subscriptions, one-time purchases, usage-based billing, or marketplace transactions. This is the revenue engine of the product. Not needed only for free products or products that handle billing entirely outside the application. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Stripe/PayPal SDK integration, checkout session creation, webhook handlers for payment events (payment_succeeded, payment_failed, subscription_updated), subscription plan database schema, pricing page UI, billing portal/settings page, invoice list and PDF generation, payment method management UI, trial tracking with expiration logic, coupon/promo code validation, dunning email flow for failed payments, and revenue reporting for the admin. EXAMPLES: A SaaS with monthly/annual subscription plans needs full billing. A marketplace needs payment processing for transactions between buyers and sellers. A usage-based tool needs metered billing with Stripe usage records. An e-learning platform needs one-time course purchases and subscription access.' WHERE feature_id = 'payments';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Role-based access control (RBAC) system that defines different permission levels for different types of users within the application. Includes predefined roles (e.g., Owner, Admin, Manager, Member, Viewer), granular permissions per role (can create, can edit, can delete, can view, can manage users), role assignment interface for admins, permission checks throughout the application UI and API, and optionally custom role creation. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for any multi-user SaaS where different users should have different levels of access. Essential for B2B SaaS with team accounts, marketplaces with buyers/sellers/admins, platforms with content creators/consumers, or any product where some users should be restricted from certain actions. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Roles and permissions database schema (roles table, permissions table, user_roles junction table), Row Level Security policies based on roles, middleware/guards for API route protection, UI conditional rendering based on user permissions, role management admin interface, invitation flow with role assignment, permission inheritance (admin inherits all member permissions), and audit log of permission changes. EXAMPLES: A project tool has Owner (full access), Admin (manage team), Member (manage tasks), and Viewer (read-only). A CRM has Sales Rep (own deals only), Manager (team deals), and Admin (all deals + settings). A content platform has Author (create/edit own), Editor (edit all), and Admin (publish + manage). A multi-tenant SaaS has Organization Owner, Department Manager, and Regular User roles.' WHERE feature_id = 'roles';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Powerful search functionality with full-text search, faceted filtering, sorting options, and paginated results. Includes a search bar with autocomplete/typeahead suggestions, multi-field search across different entities, filter panels with checkboxes/dropdowns/ranges, sorting by multiple criteria (date, relevance, price, name), paginated results with configurable page size, saved search/filter presets, and search result highlighting. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Important for any SaaS with significant amounts of content or data that users need to find quickly — marketplaces with many listings, CRMs with large contact databases, content platforms with many articles/posts, project tools with many tasks, or any application where scrolling through lists is impractical. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Full-text search implementation (PostgreSQL tsvector/tsquery or Elasticsearch), search index configuration, typeahead/autocomplete component with debounced API calls, filter UI components (multi-select, range sliders, date pickers), URL-based filter state for shareable/bookmarkable searches, search result ranking algorithm, pagination component with page size selector, and optionally saved search functionality with notification on new matches. EXAMPLES: A marketplace needs search with filters for category, price range, location, and rating. A CRM needs contact search across name, email, company, and tags. A job board needs search with filters for role, location, salary, and experience level. A knowledge base needs full-text search across articles with category filters.' WHERE feature_id = 'search';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'File upload, storage, and management system allowing users to upload, organize, preview, and download files within the application. Includes drag-and-drop file upload with progress indicators, support for multiple file types (images, PDFs, documents, spreadsheets), file size validation and type restriction, cloud storage integration (Supabase Storage, AWS S3, Google Cloud Storage), file preview for common formats (images, PDFs), file organization with folders or tags, download functionality, and secure access control (only authorized users can access files). WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for any SaaS where users need to attach, share, or manage files — document management systems, project tools with attachments, marketplaces with product images, HR platforms with resumes, real estate platforms with property photos, or any product that handles user-generated content beyond text. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: File upload component with drag-and-drop and click-to-browse, upload progress bar, client-side file validation (size, type), cloud storage bucket configuration with proper access policies, signed URL generation for secure file access, image optimization/resizing on upload, file metadata storage in database (name, size, type, URL, uploaded_by), file preview components for images and PDFs, bulk upload support, and storage quota management per user/organization. EXAMPLES: A project tool needs file attachments on tasks and comments. A real estate platform needs multiple photo uploads per listing. An HR platform needs resume/document uploads for candidates. A design collaboration tool needs file upload with version history.' WHERE feature_id = 'fileUpload';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Live data synchronization system that pushes updates to connected clients in real-time without requiring page refresh. Uses WebSocket connections or Server-Sent Events (SSE) to deliver instant updates when data changes — new messages appear immediately, status changes reflect instantly across all viewers, and collaborative edits are visible in real-time. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Important for any SaaS where multiple users may be viewing or editing the same data simultaneously, or where timely information delivery is critical. Essential for chat/messaging features, live dashboards, collaborative editing, notification systems, live activity feeds, auction/bidding platforms, or any feature where stale data creates a poor user experience. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: WebSocket or SSE connection management, Supabase Realtime subscriptions or custom WebSocket server, connection state handling (connected/disconnected/reconnecting), optimistic UI updates with server reconciliation, presence indicators (who is online/viewing), real-time event broadcasting, connection heartbeat/keep-alive, automatic reconnection with exponential backoff, and bandwidth optimization (only send changed data). EXAMPLES: A chat application shows new messages instantly without refresh. A project board updates task positions in real-time when teammates drag cards. A live dashboard refreshes metrics as new data arrives. A customer support tool shows when agents are typing and new tickets appear instantly.' WHERE feature_id = 'realtime';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Configurable business process automation system with customizable multi-step workflows, status transitions, approval chains, and automated actions triggered by state changes. Includes workflow designer/configuration (either visual or form-based), status/stage definitions with allowed transitions, automated actions on status change (send email, update fields, create tasks), approval workflows with designated approvers, conditional branching based on data values, SLA tracking with deadline enforcement, and workflow templates for common processes. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for B2B SaaS products that digitize business processes — HR tools (hiring pipeline, onboarding), CRMs (sales pipeline, deal stages), support tools (ticket escalation), project management (task lifecycle), procurement (purchase approval), or any product where items move through defined stages with rules and automations at each step. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Workflow definition schema (stages, transitions, actions, conditions), state machine implementation for valid transitions, automated action execution engine (email triggers, field updates, webhook calls), approval queue with approve/reject actions, workflow history/audit trail, SLA timer with deadline notifications, conditional logic evaluator for branching, workflow template library, and visual workflow status indicator (e.g., Kanban board or pipeline view). EXAMPLES: An HR tool has a hiring workflow: Applied → Screening → Interview → Offer → Hired, with automated emails at each stage. A CRM has a sales pipeline: Lead → Qualified → Proposal → Negotiation → Closed, with manager approval required above $50K. A support tool has ticket workflow: New → Assigned → In Progress → Resolved → Closed, with SLA escalation after 24 hours.' WHERE feature_id = 'workflows';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Advanced report generation system with custom report builder, scheduled report delivery, and multiple export formats. Goes beyond basic reporting by allowing users to create their own reports by selecting data fields, applying filters, choosing grouping/aggregation, and selecting visualization types. Includes report scheduling (daily/weekly/monthly delivery via email), export to multiple formats (PDF, CSV, Excel, PNG), saved report templates, and report sharing with team members. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Important for B2B SaaS where customers need to generate custom reports for stakeholders, compliance, or decision-making. Essential for financial software, HR platforms, project management tools, and any product where users need to extract and present data in formatted reports. Not needed for consumer apps or simple tools where the basic analytics dashboard is sufficient. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Report builder UI with field selector, filter configurator, and grouping options, chart/table visualization selector, report template save/load functionality, PDF generation engine (jsPDF, Puppeteer), CSV/Excel export utility, email scheduling system (cron jobs) for automated report delivery, report sharing with permission controls, and report versioning/history. EXAMPLES: A financial SaaS lets users build monthly P&L reports and schedule them for the first of each month. An HR platform generates headcount reports by department with trend charts. A project tool creates sprint velocity reports comparing planned vs. actual story points. A sales platform generates pipeline reports grouped by region, stage, and rep.' WHERE feature_id = 'advancedReporting';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Integration with email marketing platforms enabling automated email campaigns, subscriber management, and audience segmentation directly from the SaaS. Includes connecting to email marketing services (Mailchimp, ConvertKit, ActiveCampaign, SendGrid Marketing), automatic subscriber sync (new users added to lists), audience segmentation based on user behavior or attributes, campaign trigger automation (e.g., send onboarding sequence when user signs up, re-engagement email after 30 days inactive), email template management, and campaign performance tracking (open rates, click rates). WHEN TO INCLUDE: Important for SaaS products that want to nurture users through email marketing — onboarding sequences, feature announcements, re-engagement campaigns, upsell campaigns, or newsletter distribution. Essential for products with freemium models (convert free to paid), marketplaces (engage buyers and sellers), and content platforms (distribute new content). TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Email marketing API integration (Mailchimp, ConvertKit, etc.), subscriber list management with automatic sync, segmentation rules engine (based on plan, activity, signup date), automation trigger definitions (event-based email sequences), email template editor or template selection, campaign analytics dashboard (sent, opened, clicked, unsubscribed), unsubscribe handling for compliance (CAN-SPAM, GDPR), and A/B testing support for subject lines and content. EXAMPLES: A SaaS sends a 5-email onboarding sequence to new users, then segments by plan tier for upsell campaigns. A marketplace sends weekly digest emails to buyers with new listings matching their interests. A content platform sends personalized content recommendations based on reading history. A B2B tool sends product update announcements segmented by feature usage.' WHERE feature_id = 'emailMarketing';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Artificial intelligence and machine learning capabilities integrated into the SaaS to provide intelligent features such as content generation, smart recommendations, predictive analytics, natural language processing, image recognition, sentiment analysis, and automated decision-making. Includes integration with AI APIs (OpenAI GPT, Anthropic Claude, Google Gemini) or custom ML models, prompt engineering for domain-specific tasks, AI-generated content with human review workflows, recommendation engines based on user behavior, predictive scoring models, and conversational AI assistants/chatbots. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Important for SaaS products that can leverage AI to provide significant value — content creation tools, customer support automation, sales intelligence, personalized recommendations, data analysis, document processing, or any domain where AI can automate repetitive cognitive tasks or surface insights humans would miss. Not needed for simple CRUD applications without a clear AI use case. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: AI/LLM API integration (OpenAI, Anthropic, etc.), prompt template management for different use cases, streaming response handling for real-time AI output, token usage tracking and cost management, AI output caching for repeated queries, human-in-the-loop review system for AI-generated content, recommendation engine with collaborative/content-based filtering, ML model training pipeline (if custom models), vector database for semantic search (if RAG), and AI usage analytics dashboard. EXAMPLES: A content marketing SaaS uses GPT to generate blog post drafts, social media captions, and email copy. A CRM uses AI to score leads based on engagement patterns and predict conversion likelihood. A customer support tool uses AI to auto-categorize tickets and suggest responses. An e-commerce platform uses ML for personalized product recommendations.' WHERE feature_id = 'ai';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Enterprise-grade data analytics platform with big data processing capabilities, advanced statistical analysis, predictive modeling, data pipeline management, and business intelligence features. Goes beyond standard analytics dashboards to offer data warehouse integration, custom metric definitions, statistical correlation analysis, anomaly detection, forecasting models, and self-service data exploration tools. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for data-intensive SaaS products that process large volumes of data and provide analytical insights as their core value proposition — business intelligence platforms, marketing analytics tools, financial analysis software, IoT data platforms, or any product where advanced data processing is a key differentiator. Not needed for standard SaaS with basic reporting needs. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Data pipeline/ETL framework for ingesting and transforming data, data warehouse or analytics database (ClickHouse, BigQuery, Redshift), custom metric definition engine with formulas, statistical analysis functions (regression, correlation, distribution), anomaly detection algorithms with alerting, time series forecasting models, data visualization library with advanced chart types (heatmaps, scatter plots, sankey diagrams), self-service query builder for non-technical users, data caching and pre-aggregation for performance, and data governance with lineage tracking. EXAMPLES: A marketing analytics platform processes millions of ad impressions to calculate attribution across channels. A financial SaaS analyzes transaction patterns to detect fraud and predict cash flow. An IoT platform aggregates sensor data from thousands of devices for predictive maintenance. A HR analytics tool correlates employee engagement data with retention and performance metrics.' WHERE feature_id = 'dataAnalytics';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Multi-tenant architecture that allows a single instance of the application to serve multiple organizations (tenants) with complete data isolation, separate configurations, and optional custom branding per tenant. Includes tenant provisioning and lifecycle management, data isolation at the database level (schema-per-tenant or row-level isolation), per-tenant configuration (feature flags, limits, branding), tenant-specific billing and subscription management, cross-tenant admin capabilities for platform operators, and tenant data export for portability. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for B2B SaaS products that serve multiple companies/organizations from a single platform — any product sold to businesses where each company needs their own isolated workspace with their own users, data, and settings. Essential for products like project management tools, HR platforms, CRMs, helpdesk software, or any tool where organizations sign up and invite their team members. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Tenant/organization database schema with unique identifiers, Row Level Security policies for tenant data isolation, tenant context middleware (resolve tenant from subdomain, URL path, or header), user-to-tenant relationship (users belong to one or more tenants), tenant-scoped queries (all data queries filtered by tenant_id), tenant provisioning flow (create organization, assign owner), per-tenant settings storage (branding, feature flags, limits), tenant-aware invitation system, cross-tenant super-admin interface, and tenant data backup/export functionality. EXAMPLES: A project management SaaS where each company has its own workspace with projects, tasks, and team members completely isolated from other companies. A helpdesk platform where each business manages their own tickets, knowledge base, and customer portal. A CRM where each sales organization has their own pipeline, contacts, and reporting.' WHERE feature_id = 'multiTenant';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Enterprise-grade security features including Single Sign-On (SSO) with SAML 2.0 and OpenID Connect (OIDC) support, comprehensive audit logging, compliance controls, advanced threat protection, and enterprise identity provider integration. Includes SSO configuration per organization (connect to Okta, Azure AD, Google Workspace), SCIM user provisioning for automated user lifecycle management, detailed audit logs for all sensitive actions, IP allowlisting, session management policies (timeout, concurrent sessions), data residency controls, and compliance certifications support (SOC 2, GDPR, HIPAA). WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for SaaS products targeting enterprise customers (companies with 500+ employees) who mandate SSO, audit logging, and compliance controls as procurement requirements. Essential when selling to regulated industries (healthcare, finance, government) or security-conscious organizations. Not needed for consumer apps or SMB-only products. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: SAML 2.0 Service Provider implementation, OIDC/OAuth 2.0 integration with enterprise IdPs, SCIM 2.0 endpoint for automated user provisioning/deprovisioning, comprehensive audit log system (who did what, when, from where), audit log search and export functionality, IP allowlist configuration per organization, session policy management (max session duration, idle timeout, max concurrent sessions), two-factor authentication enforcement per organization, data encryption key management, and compliance report generation. EXAMPLES: A B2B SaaS integrates with Okta so enterprise employees log in with their corporate credentials. A healthcare SaaS implements HIPAA audit logging for all patient data access. A financial platform enforces IP allowlisting and session timeouts for compliance. An enterprise tool uses SCIM to automatically provision/deprovision users when employees join or leave the company.' WHERE feature_id = 'sso';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Custom-built integration layer for connecting the SaaS with proprietary, legacy, or non-standard external systems that don not have pre-built connectors. Includes a flexible integration framework with custom API adapters, data transformation pipelines, webhook-based event system for pushing/receiving data, custom ETL processes, API development for third-party consumption, and integration monitoring with error handling. Goes beyond standard third-party API integrations by supporting custom protocols, legacy system adapters, and complex data mapping. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for enterprise SaaS products whose customers need to connect with their existing internal systems — legacy ERPs, proprietary databases, industry-specific software, government systems, or custom-built tools. Also needed when the SaaS itself needs to offer an API for customers to build their own integrations. Essential for products selling into enterprises with complex IT landscapes. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Custom API adapter framework with pluggable connectors, webhook system (both outgoing and incoming) with retry logic, data transformation/mapping engine for converting between formats, integration configuration UI per customer, integration health monitoring dashboard, error queue with manual retry capability, API documentation generator (OpenAPI/Swagger), rate limiting and throttling per integration, integration testing sandbox, and secure credential storage for customer API keys. EXAMPLES: A supply chain SaaS connects with customers legacy ERP systems via custom SOAP/XML adapters. A healthcare platform integrates with hospital HL7/FHIR systems through custom protocol handlers. An enterprise tool provides a REST API so customers can build custom integrations with their internal tools. A logistics SaaS connects with various carrier APIs (FedEx, UPS, DHL) through custom adapters.' WHERE feature_id = 'customIntegrations';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Comprehensive API management platform providing full control over the SaaS public and internal APIs. Includes API gateway with request routing, API versioning strategy (URL-based or header-based), rate limiting and throttling per client/plan, API key management and rotation, comprehensive API documentation with interactive playground, API usage analytics and monitoring, developer portal for third-party developers, and API deprecation lifecycle management. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for platform-type SaaS products that expose APIs for third-party developers, partner integrations, or customer-built extensions. Essential when the product has a developer ecosystem, offers a public API as a product feature, or needs to manage multiple API versions simultaneously. Also important for products with usage-based API billing. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: API gateway layer with request routing and middleware, API versioning system with backward compatibility, rate limiter with configurable limits per API key/plan tier, API key generation and management interface, OAuth 2.0 server for API authentication, OpenAPI/Swagger specification auto-generation, interactive API documentation portal (Swagger UI, Redoc), API usage tracking and analytics dashboard, webhook management for API consumers, API sandbox/testing environment, and deprecation notices with migration guides. EXAMPLES: A data platform provides a public REST API with rate limits based on subscription tier. A payment SaaS manages API versions (v1, v2) with deprecation timelines. A communication platform offers developer APIs with SDKs and a developer portal. An analytics SaaS provides API access with usage-based billing and real-time usage dashboards.' WHERE feature_id = 'apiManagement';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Real-time collaboration features enabling multiple users to work together simultaneously on shared content or data. Includes real-time co-editing (multiple cursors, live text updates), commenting and annotation system with @mentions, threaded discussions on specific items, activity feeds showing team actions, presence indicators (who is online, who is viewing/editing), collaborative cursors and selections, change tracking with version history, and conflict resolution for simultaneous edits. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for SaaS products where teamwork and shared workspaces are core to the value proposition — document editors, design tools, project management platforms, whiteboarding tools, spreadsheet applications, or any product where multiple people need to contribute to the same artifact simultaneously. Also important for products where team communication around shared objects is a key workflow. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Operational Transformation (OT) or CRDT algorithm for conflict-free concurrent editing, WebSocket connections for real-time data sync, presence system (user online status, current location in document), collaborative cursor rendering, commenting system with @mention notifications, activity feed with real-time updates, version history with diff view and rollback capability, change attribution (who changed what), notification system for mentions and replies, and optimistic concurrency control for non-real-time collaborative features. EXAMPLES: A document editor like Google Docs where multiple users type simultaneously with visible cursors. A design tool where team members comment on specific areas of a mockup. A project management tool where team members discuss tasks in threaded comments with @mentions. A spreadsheet application where multiple users edit cells simultaneously with conflict resolution.' WHERE feature_id = 'collaboration';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Sophisticated automation engine with complex rule definitions, multi-condition triggers, scheduled tasks, event-driven workflows, and automated actions across the entire application. Goes beyond simple workflows by offering conditional logic trees (if/then/else), multi-step automation chains, time-based scheduling (cron), event-based triggers from any system action, external webhook triggers, automated data transformations, and batch processing capabilities. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for SaaS products where users want to eliminate repetitive manual tasks through customizable automation rules — marketing automation platforms, CRMs with lead scoring, operations tools with process automation, DevOps platforms, or any product where power users want to create their own automation rules without coding. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Automation rule builder UI (trigger → conditions → actions), event bus for capturing all system events as potential triggers, condition evaluator with AND/OR/NOT logic and comparison operators, action executor supporting multiple action types (send email, update record, call webhook, create task), scheduled task runner with cron syntax, automation execution log with debugging information, automation templates library, rate limiting and execution quotas per plan, error handling with retry policies, and automation testing/preview mode before activation. EXAMPLES: A CRM automatically scores leads based on email opens + website visits + form submissions, then assigns hot leads to senior reps. A marketing tool automatically segments users who haven not logged in for 30 days and triggers a re-engagement email sequence. An e-commerce platform automatically adjusts pricing based on inventory levels and competitor prices. A project tool automatically creates follow-up tasks when a deadline is missed and notifies the manager.' WHERE feature_id = 'automation';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Flexible, user-facing report builder engine that allows end-users to create fully custom reports without technical knowledge. Includes drag-and-drop report designer with field selection from any data source, custom formulas and calculated fields, multiple visualization types (tables, charts, pivot tables, KPI cards), cross-entity data joins, parameterized filters, report templates, white-label PDF export with custom branding, report embedding via iframe, and report access control. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for B2B SaaS products whose customers have diverse and unpredictable reporting needs that cannot be satisfied by pre-built dashboards alone. Essential for enterprise software, analytics platforms, ERP systems, and any product where each customer needs different views of their data. This is the most sophisticated reporting capability and should only be included when customers explicitly need self-service report creation. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Visual report builder with drag-and-drop interface, data source connector layer (map database tables/views to user-friendly field names), formula engine for calculated fields (SUM, AVG, COUNT, custom expressions), pivot table component with row/column grouping, chart builder with multiple visualization types, filter builder with parameter inputs, report layout designer with sections and formatting, PDF/Excel export with custom branding/logo, report scheduling with email delivery, report sharing with granular permissions, embedded report viewer component, and report version history. EXAMPLES: A SaaS ERP lets finance teams build custom P&L statements with their own account groupings and formulas. An HR platform lets each department create their own headcount and compensation reports. A logistics SaaS lets operations managers build custom delivery performance reports by region, driver, and time period. A CRM lets sales managers create pipeline reports with custom stages, fields, and calculations specific to their sales process.' WHERE feature_id = 'customReporting';

UPDATE public.tb_pms_mvp_features SET feature_description = 'Enterprise-grade customer support infrastructure built into the SaaS, including a ticketing system, Service Level Agreement (SLA) management, knowledge base/help center, live chat widget, customer communication history, support agent dashboard, and self-service support portal. Provides both the internal tools for the support team and the customer-facing support experience. WHEN TO INCLUDE: Required for SaaS products that need structured customer support operations — especially B2B products with paying customers who expect reliable support channels. Essential when the product serves enterprise clients with SLA requirements, when support volume justifies a dedicated system, or when self-service documentation is needed to reduce support load. Not needed for early-stage MVPs that handle support via email or a simple contact form. TECHNICAL COMPONENTS: Ticket creation and management system with status workflow (New → Open → Pending → Resolved → Closed), SLA configuration with response time and resolution time targets, SLA breach alerting and escalation rules, knowledge base CMS with categories, search, and article versioning, live chat widget with agent assignment and queue management, customer portal for ticket submission and status tracking, canned responses/macros for common issues, support analytics dashboard (response times, resolution rates, CSAT scores), multi-channel support intake (email, chat, form), agent workload balancing, and customer satisfaction survey integration. EXAMPLES: A B2B SaaS provides a help center with searchable articles plus a ticketing system with 4-hour response SLA for enterprise clients. A platform offers live chat support during business hours with automatic ticket creation for off-hours messages. An enterprise tool provides a customer portal where users submit and track support requests with SLA visibility. A SaaS product includes a knowledge base that reduces ticket volume by 40% through self-service documentation.' WHERE feature_id = 'support';
